## Design decisions, explained

### Why the algorithm is a true sliding window

| Property | Fixed window | This implementation |
|---|---|---|
| Reset trigger | Clock ticks to next interval | Each request recomputes relative to `Date.now()` |
| Burst at boundary | Up to 2× `maxRequests` at seam | Impossible — window is always `[now − windowMs, now]` |
| Memory per IP | O(1) — just a counter | O(k) where k = requests in current window |

The trade-off is memory: O(k) per IP vs O(1) for a fixed window. For typical values (`maxRequests = 100`, `windowMs = 60 s`) that's at most a few hundred bytes per active IP — entirely negligible.

### `Retry-After` precision

When rejecting, `timestamps[0]` (the **oldest** timestamp still inside the window) tells us exactly when one slot will open:

```
retryAfter = ceil((timestamps[0] + windowMs - now) / 1000)
```

This is tighter than returning the full `windowMs` remaining — the client can retry sooner than a naïve implementation would suggest.

### `X-RateLimit-Reset`

Set to the epoch second when `timestamps[0]` exits the window. For the very first request in a fresh window `timestamps[0]` is the current request itself, so `Reset` is `now + windowMs` — correct.

### Memory management

The `setInterval` cleanup is `.unref()`-ed so it never prevents the process from exiting. `close()` gives callers an explicit way to clear it during graceful shutdown or in test teardown (`afterAll(() => limiter.close())`).

